2022 was a difficult year but lots of great memories.

I went through a difficult journey of coparenting. Lots of changes that has made me have to look at life differently but I survived it.

I lost the biggest contract of my career, had my name tarnished, government disregarded the facts and I walked away from my career. I survived it. 

I got the opportunity to take my girls to Disney World. I was on a high of laughs, love, fun! Best time of my life and I was financially able to do it by myself! I survived it.

I survived that day and the next day and the next day and the next…

My survival bag is filled with consistent learning… because to get better, you must be learning through each lesson.

The journey continues… what is in your survival bag for 2023?

If you don’t know much about trauma and how it is stored in the hips- you are about to learn today.

I saw a post by a therapist who teaches her clients to move their hips, dance- in order to release trauma and the emotions stored within the body. Remarkably the hips hold much of the emotions that are experienced on a neuro- cellular level.

Yeah the easiest movement like these 90:90s might be silly to do, but when I program them into my mobility training- I realize that after I do them, I’m smiling. I’m lighter, softer— and we all need that soft feminine to rise during times our masculine takes over!

Add these into your regimen babes- elevate your mood all 2023!

Did you know your quads and hips being tight can not only cause low back pain but core and pelvic floor issues?

Yes, the body is so connected that 1 muscle can truly impact another and another and the list goes on.

Tight hip flexors cause compensation patterns in the low back and over time because the back is intended to stabilize your body, your core gets weaker when these imbalances exist. 

So stretching can be helpful and my favorite is this movement because it targets the hips, quads and gives the low back a good little release at the same time you will feel your core activate during this stretch! A win for the whole body.

Try holding position for 1-2 min and no need to do this daily. 5 min stretching weekly is all you need to start. So 2 min each for 3 days for example. 

Give it try and tag a mom friend to share this with

How to heal your mommy tummy or #diastasis recti for most:

1) you must learn the basics first and stop jumping on the bandwagon of the quick fix on instagram 

Basics include: diaphragmatic breathing, re-connect with your pelvic floor muscles, get to know your weakness if any and your strengths (which you do have)

Mommas it’s no secret- the word has been out— 

YOU HAVE A DIASTASIS RECTI!
It’s the separation of your abdominal muscles most commonly effected during pregnancy because of your growing baby, movement, and abdominal pressure management.
Some women can have a functional DR meaning less then 2 fingers wide and strong fascial tissue that responds to movement pretty well.

While others can have an injury based DR that is greater then 3 fingers width and lack of fascia response, so all your belly pressure during movement goes straight to the weakest point (your diastasis recti). During exercise, daily activity, and intimacy your diastasis can effect it’s healing process.

One thing I’ve learned by helping women all over the US and internationally is this- every body is different and there is no 1 size fit all approach. Diastasis recti repair is also not really sexy (let’s be honest) but rehab of your core and body can help you see your body’s potential and your body’s abilities when you do it the right way! 

Fit Healing is a 2 system approach: we start with healing through the foundation work which is the not so sexy part and then we apply the fitness, the advancement into functional movement, strength based exercise and muscle endurance.

This approach is not a 4 week or 6 week recovery process but based on each persons lifestyle and body is different.

Pregnancy can bring a lot of different changes to your body and one of those changes is FATIGUE. 

Hormone changes play a big role in making you feel tired, especially the hormone progesterone. This hormone rises sharply in the first trimester. In addition, as blood volume increases to supply the developing placenta and fetal circulation, your heart pumps faster and stronger.

As we began the New Year- here is how I’m prepping my January mamas for labor: WAYS TO HELP DECREASE TEARING 🫶🏽

1) Use a warm compress: clean of course- Your doula and nurse can assist with this during the Big Push. A warm compress helps the blood flow in the area allowing the tissue and skin to stretch.

2) try to avoid laboring on your back and delivery in this position as this position decreases the space for your coccyx to move and help with the rotation of baby’s head.

3) knees in ankles out- mobility is key for labor!

To begin at 35 weeks you want to use clean hands and raw coconut oil not lub€. Use two fingers to create u shape stretching gently the vulva parts down to rectum. You can hold toward rectum for 60 seconds.

It’s never too late to start but you want to start to decrease tearing!

I experienced this recently with a new mom and this is possible. Mom had labored for 6 hours and dilated to 9cm. Doctor checks mom and baby is at station -1. Well it’s not time to PUSh and mom is tired from taking all the contraction discomfort so we set her up in the cowgirl position. Yes, while lying, the key is hips forward but not overarching back, this helps baby continue progressing down while mommy focuses on maintaining breath to mind on her contractions.
